1
00:00:46,813 --> 00:00:49,115
[BIRDS CHIRPING]

2
00:01:11,071 --> 00:01:12,975
[BANGING]

3
00:01:25,786 --> 00:01:27,420
- And so, heh...
- Heh.

4
00:01:27,421 --> 00:01:32,329
I chose jellyfish as my favorite...

5
00:01:34,227 --> 00:01:36,529
[BABY COOING]

6
00:01:44,037 --> 00:01:46,339
[CHICKENS CLUCKING]

7
00:03:00,213 --> 00:03:02,014
You all fed? Yeah?

8
00:03:02,015 --> 00:03:04,295
Yeah...

9
00:03:25,872 --> 00:03:28,174
[FOOTSTEPS]

10
00:03:40,554 --> 00:03:42,333
[DOOR CLOSES]

11
00:04:23,196 --> 00:04:25,237
[DOOR OPENS]

12
00:04:25,899 --> 00:04:29,935
[MAN]:
Marcy! Marcy May!

13
00:04:29,936 --> 00:04:32,113
Where you going?

14
00:04:32,706 --> 00:04:34,576
[DOOR CLOSES]

15
00:04:44,584 --> 00:04:46,886
[PANTING]

16
00:05:11,478 --> 00:05:14,258
[FOOTSTEPS RUNNING]

17
00:05:38,672 --> 00:05:40,974
[DOOR BELL JINGLING]

18
00:05:53,220 --> 00:05:57,022
[WATTS]:
Marcy, what are you doing here?

19
00:05:57,023 --> 00:05:59,428
Worried about you.

20
00:06:00,861 --> 00:06:03,163
Well, I'm fine.

21
00:06:04,030 --> 00:06:08,506
Yeah? And Patrick is worried about you.

22
00:06:08,802 --> 00:06:10,809
I just wanted to come into town.

23
00:06:11,538 --> 00:06:14,216
Oh, I could have given you a ride.

24
00:06:14,307 --> 00:06:16,075
I wanted to walk.

25
00:06:16,076 --> 00:06:18,117
Through the woods?

26
00:06:21,414 --> 00:06:23,048
Can I get you something?

27
00:06:23,049 --> 00:06:25,556
No, thank you.

28
00:06:25,719 --> 00:06:27,623
Are you done?

29
00:06:27,687 --> 00:06:29,688
Yeah.
Uh...

30
00:06:29,689 --> 00:06:31,900
You're not gonna finish that?

31
00:06:32,325 --> 00:06:34,366
Okay, thanks.

32
00:06:42,769 --> 00:06:44,139
Mm.

33
00:06:57,717 --> 00:06:59,585
Ready to go?

34
00:06:59,586 --> 00:07:01,729
Not right now.

35
00:07:03,723 --> 00:07:05,400
No?

36
00:07:18,204 --> 00:07:21,383
Hey, don't do that. Come here.

37
00:07:24,444 --> 00:07:26,378
You're shaking.

38
00:07:26,379 --> 00:07:28,420
Calm down.

39
00:07:32,585 --> 00:07:35,388
All right. You take care of yourself.

40
00:07:51,638 --> 00:07:55,215
[LINE RINGING]

41
00:08:00,013 --> 00:08:01,951
[WOMAN OVER PHONE]:
Hello?

42
00:08:03,249 --> 00:08:06,120
<i>He. Ho?</i>

43
00:08:08,655 --> 00:08:11,824
<i>- Martha?
- Yeah.</i>

44
00:08:11,825 --> 00:08:15,231
<i>Where are you? Where have you been?</i>

45
00:08:17,330 --> 00:08:22,801
Uh, I'm not sure. I'm upstate, I think.

46
00:08:22,802 --> 00:08:24,670
<i>You're in New York?</i>

47
00:08:24,671 --> 00:08:26,972
Yeah, I think.

48
00:08:26,973 --> 00:08:29,274
<i>When did you get back?</i>

49
00:08:29,275 --> 00:08:31,816
<i>How long have you been here?</i>

50
00:08:32,712 --> 00:08:34,616
Martha?

51
00:08:34,848 --> 00:08:36,849
<i>Martha, what's wrong?</i>

52
00:08:36,850 --> 00:08:39,351
I don't know. Um...

53
00:08:39,352 --> 00:08:42,287
I should go back.

54
00:08:42,288 --> 00:08:44,590
<i>Go back where?</i>

55
00:08:45,291 --> 00:08:49,061
<i>Martha, what happened? Are you okay?</i>

56
00:08:49,062 --> 00:08:52,631
Um, I have to go. Um...

57
00:08:52,632 --> 00:08:54,533
I can't stay gone, so...

58
00:08:54,534 --> 00:08:56,235
<i>No, no, no, don't go.</i>

59
00:08:56,236 --> 00:08:58,709
<i>What are you talking about?</i>

60
00:09:00,507 --> 00:09:02,309
<i>Martha.</i>

61
00:09:02,375 --> 00:09:03,876
I'm sorry for calling.

62
00:09:03,877 --> 00:09:06,311
<i>Please don't hang up.
Don't hang up the phone.</i>

63
00:09:06,312 --> 00:09:09,286
<i>Find out where you are
and! will come get you.</i>

64
00:09:11,584 --> 00:09:14,386
Martha?
I can't wait that long.

65
00:09:14,387 --> 00:09:17,656
<i>What do you mean? Tell me where you are
and I will come right now.</i>

66
00:09:17,657 --> 00:09:20,225
No, it's okay, you don't have to.

67
00:09:20,226 --> 00:09:23,530
<i>Martha, I wanna see you. Please.</i>

68
00:09:23,897 --> 00:09:25,835
Martha?

69
00:09:26,332 --> 00:09:28,305
<i>Martha.</i>

70
00:09:42,348 --> 00:09:44,184
[CAR DOOR CLOSES]

71
00:09:58,765 --> 00:10:01,671
I made you some tea.
Thanks.

72
00:10:06,773 --> 00:10:10,179
You're dripping everywhere.

73
00:10:15,615 --> 00:10:19,118
Ted should be up from the city soon,
make us some dinner.

74
00:10:19,119 --> 00:10:20,619
I'm pretty tired.

75
00:10:20,620 --> 00:10:23,457
Is it okay if I just go to bed?

76
00:10:25,658 --> 00:10:27,437
Sure.

77
00:10:28,294 --> 00:10:32,132
Get a good night's sleep tonight
and you'll be as good as new tomorrow.

78
00:10:44,978 --> 00:10:46,552
[DOOR CLOSES]

79
00:10:49,616 --> 00:10:51,486
[SIGHS]

80
00:10:58,825 --> 00:11:00,627
[DOOR OPENS]

81
00:11:03,163 --> 00:11:04,596
[DOOR CLOSES]

82
00:11:04,597 --> 00:11:07,309
- Hi.
- [TED]: Hey.

83
00:11:10,303 --> 00:11:11,809
<i>Hey'...</i>

84
00:11:16,342 --> 00:11:20,112
- Well?
- She seems okay.

85
00:11:21,447 --> 00:11:23,882
What did she say?
Not much.

86
00:11:23,883 --> 00:11:25,651
She's really tired.

87
00:11:25,652 --> 00:11:26,985
- Yeah?
- Yeah.

88
00:11:26,986 --> 00:11:29,027
Where's she been?

89
00:11:29,189 --> 00:11:32,491
She had some boyfriend.
They were living in the Catskills.

90
00:11:32,492 --> 00:11:35,027
- What?
- It's okay.

91
00:11:35,028 --> 00:11:37,362
Heh, it's not really, Lucy.
It's fine.

92
00:11:37,363 --> 00:11:40,032
She's here now.

93
00:11:40,033 --> 00:11:41,971
Hmm.

94
00:11:43,069 --> 00:11:45,849
- How long is she gonna be staying again?
- Ha-ha-ha!

95
00:11:52,045 --> 00:11:54,188
[TED]:
Oh, Martha.

96
00:11:55,748 --> 00:11:58,392
- Welcome.
- Hi.

97
00:12:00,220 --> 00:12:03,399
- Great to finally meet you.
- Yeah.

98
00:12:04,023 --> 00:12:06,058
- Did you sleep all right?
- Mm-hm.

99
00:12:06,059 --> 00:12:07,702
Good.

100
00:12:08,061 --> 00:12:10,429
So how do you like our house?

101
00:12:10,430 --> 00:12:12,641
It's nice.

102
00:12:13,833 --> 00:12:17,002
It's just a rental.
Yeah, well, I love it.

103
00:12:17,003 --> 00:12:18,976
Mm.

104
00:12:19,505 --> 00:12:23,651
<i>I didn't know there was a lake.
Mm. Yeah.</i>

105
00:12:23,943 --> 00:12:25,677
Do you still like to swim?

106
00:12:25,678 --> 00:12:28,113
- You don't still live in the city?
- [TED & LUCY]: Heh, heh.

107
00:12:28,114 --> 00:12:32,362
We do. We just like to come up here
on weekends and holidays.

108
00:12:36,756 --> 00:12:39,691
You know. Ted is working
on this new building downtown...

109
00:12:39,692 --> 00:12:41,426
and as soon as it's finished...

110
00:12:41,427 --> 00:12:44,867
we're taking one of the apartments.
Do you wanna see pictures?

111
00:12:47,100 --> 00:12:50,040
Do you think she's excited
to have you back?

112
00:12:52,071 --> 00:12:55,607
This is just the view, and obviously
the interiors aren't finished...

113
00:12:55,608 --> 00:12:58,855
- but it's nice, right?
- [MARTHA]: Mm-hm.

114
00:12:59,145 --> 00:13:01,446
We were supposed to move in
in the spring...

115
00:13:01,447 --> 00:13:05,150
but, uh, construction was halted, so
it's gonna be just a little while longer.

116
00:13:05,151 --> 00:13:10,400
Yes, just a little while longer.
Okay, sorry, no more work talk.

117
00:13:12,892 --> 00:13:15,069
Aren't you hungry?

118
00:13:15,395 --> 00:13:18,096
Not really, sorry.
Well, you have to eat something.

119
00:13:18,097 --> 00:13:21,708
It's okay,
I can make you something later.

120
00:13:28,341 --> 00:13:30,450
Where are we?

121
00:13:30,476 --> 00:13:32,449
Connecticut.

122
00:13:35,315 --> 00:13:37,595
Well, how far are we?

123
00:13:38,318 --> 00:13:40,996
From what?
Yesterday.

124
00:13:43,756 --> 00:13:46,559
You mean from where I picked you up?

125
00:13:47,660 --> 00:13:50,497
About three hours. Why?

126
00:13:50,930 --> 00:13:52,971
I was just wondering.

127
00:13:57,003 --> 00:13:59,305
[HAMMER BANGING]

128
00:14:04,177 --> 00:14:06,479
[HAMMER BANGING]

129
00:14:11,484 --> 00:14:13,318
Put out your cigarette.
Why?

130
00:14:13,319 --> 00:14:15,257
Just do it.

131
00:14:16,856 --> 00:14:18,390
Is that him?
Yeah.

132
00:14:18,391 --> 00:14:19,858
<i>Hey'...</i>

133
00:14:19,859 --> 00:14:21,293
[PATRICK]:
Is this Martha?

134
00:14:21,294 --> 00:14:22,937
Hi.

135
00:14:23,129 --> 00:14:25,964
- How you doing?
- Great.

136
00:14:25,965 --> 00:14:28,967
Oh, you've got a really nice place here.

137
00:14:28,968 --> 00:14:32,010
It's as much yours as it is mine.

138
00:14:32,038 --> 00:14:35,073
- I thought you quit.
- I did.

139
00:14:35,074 --> 00:14:36,908
I worry for you.

140
00:14:36,909 --> 00:14:38,779
I know.

141
00:14:40,880 --> 00:14:43,023
I'm sorry.

142
00:14:43,349 --> 00:14:46,528
Don't apologize to me. It's your body.

143
00:14:50,690 --> 00:14:54,993
Zoe, look after this girl.

144
00:14:54,994 --> 00:14:58,263
For once in her life,
she deserves some real care.

145
00:14:58,264 --> 00:14:59,564
I will.

146
00:14:59,565 --> 00:15:01,666
She's been great.

147
00:15:01,667 --> 00:15:05,380
Everyone's been really great.
Good.

148
00:15:06,439 --> 00:15:08,548
Martha.

149
00:15:10,543 --> 00:15:13,221
You look like a Marcy May.

150
00:15:13,246 --> 00:15:14,913
Marcy was my grandmother's name.

151
00:15:14,914 --> 00:15:17,888
Wow, there you go.
Heh.

152
00:15:24,891 --> 00:15:27,092
[TED]: I'm going in.
Do you wanna join'?

153
00:15:27,093 --> 00:15:28,895
Sure.

154
00:15:31,697 --> 00:15:35,342
- You coming?
- In a minute.

155
00:16:22,915 --> 00:16:25,161
Martha!

156
00:16:35,795 --> 00:16:38,196
That is an interesting choice
of swim wear.

157
00:16:38,197 --> 00:16:40,477
Martha, get out of the water.

158
00:16:41,000 --> 00:16:43,001
- What?
- [LUCY]: Get out of the water.

159
00:16:43,002 --> 00:16:45,937
Why aren't you wearing any clothes?
What is wrong with you?

160
00:16:45,938 --> 00:16:48,306
- You can't do that around here, you know.
- [MARTHA]: Why?

161
00:16:48,307 --> 00:16:50,542
Because there are kids around.
People come by.

162
00:16:50,543 --> 00:16:53,011
- [MARTHA]: So?
- You just can't, OK? Get outta the water.

163
00:16:53,012 --> 00:16:55,656
We don't do that kind of thing.
Get out.

164
00:16:58,684 --> 00:17:01,853
You could have asked me.
I have a bathing suit you could borrow.

165
00:17:01,854 --> 00:17:04,498
What's wrong with you?
Jesus.

166
00:18:23,703 --> 00:18:24,970
[MAX]:
Hey, hey, Marcy.

167
00:18:24,971 --> 00:18:26,438
- Max.
- [MAX]: Hey.

168
00:18:26,439 --> 00:18:28,473
- Where do they go at night?
- Uh...

169
00:18:28,474 --> 00:18:32,244
Pfft! I don't know. Heh.
I never get invited.

170
00:18:37,483 --> 00:18:40,059
You wanna have a drink with me?

171
00:18:40,620 --> 00:18:42,320
They won't be back for a few hours.

172
00:18:42,321 --> 00:18:44,661
I shouldn't.
I'm not gonna drink for a while, actually.

173
00:18:44,662 --> 00:18:46,962
I think it's a good idea for me.

174
00:18:47,126 --> 00:18:48,928
All right.

175
00:18:50,796 --> 00:18:52,871
[GRUNTS]

176
00:18:55,401 --> 00:18:58,545
[CLANGING]

177
00:18:58,738 --> 00:19:01,211
Wake up, everybody.

178
00:19:04,276 --> 00:19:06,249
Good morning.

179
00:19:37,977 --> 00:19:43,181
We switch out jobs each day
so we all know how to do different things.

180
00:19:43,182 --> 00:19:45,350
Do you knit?
No.

181
00:19:45,351 --> 00:19:47,686
I can learn, though.
Oh, no, that's okay.

182
00:19:47,687 --> 00:19:49,721
You'll find your role.

183
00:19:49,722 --> 00:19:54,164
It takes time for people
to find their role in a new family.

184
00:19:55,461 --> 00:19:59,397
Mostly, we sell blankets in town
because we still need some money.

185
00:19:59,398 --> 00:20:03,334
But once the farm is up and running,
we'll be self-sufficient...

186
00:20:03,335 --> 00:20:06,673
and we'll never have
to worry about it again.

187
00:20:07,640 --> 00:20:11,183
[HUMMING]

188
00:20:25,024 --> 00:20:26,725
Hey. I'm sorry, Patrick. Hey.

189
00:20:26,726 --> 00:20:29,194
- [PATRICK]: What're you sorry for'?
- Ahem.

190
00:20:29,195 --> 00:20:31,372
Um, here.

191
00:20:31,430 --> 00:20:33,098
How are you, man?

192
00:20:33,099 --> 00:20:34,666
Good, you?

193
00:20:34,667 --> 00:20:36,571
Feels like...

194
00:20:37,103 --> 00:20:40,438
- It's a really great consistency.
- [ZOE]: Yeah, and it's sticky.

195
00:20:40,439 --> 00:20:43,508
And it holds together like glue.

196
00:20:43,509 --> 00:20:46,611
- And it can flow around. Like...
- [WATTS]: You should talk to her.

197
00:20:46,612 --> 00:20:48,880
That's why I need to
figure out how to do it.

198
00:20:48,881 --> 00:20:50,353
Yeah.

199
00:20:50,516 --> 00:20:53,618
Yeah, you'll figure it out. Don't look...

200
00:20:53,619 --> 00:20:56,866
[PATRICK]: How's everything
going so far, Marcy May?

201
00:20:56,889 --> 00:20:59,591
- Good.
- [PATRICK]: Do you like it here?

202
00:20:59,592 --> 00:21:02,060
Yeah, it's... it's great.

203
00:21:02,061 --> 00:21:03,728
[PATRICK]:
I want you to feel at home.

204
00:21:03,729 --> 00:21:07,272
- I do, thank you.
- [PATRICK]: Mm-hm.

205
00:21:07,433 --> 00:21:09,934
I know people have abandoned you
your whole life.

206
00:21:09,935 --> 00:21:12,738
- Your father.
- What?

207
00:21:12,772 --> 00:21:15,746
I don't blame you
for not trusting people.

208
00:21:17,576 --> 00:21:21,085
But if you're ever going to have
a meaningful relationship...

209
00:21:21,614 --> 00:21:24,121
you need to let your guard down.

210
00:21:24,650 --> 00:21:27,396
It's not your fault, but it's there.

211
00:21:28,387 --> 00:21:32,362
And if you feel safe here,
and I hope you do, let us in.

212
00:21:33,292 --> 00:21:35,435
We wanna help you.

213
00:21:35,461 --> 00:21:39,299
Yeah. We think you're fucking awesome.

214
00:21:39,732 --> 00:21:42,239
[PATRICK]:
But if you're gonna live here...

215
00:21:43,803 --> 00:21:46,379
you need to be a part of things.

216
00:21:58,484 --> 00:21:59,818
Play another song.

217
00:21:59,819 --> 00:22:02,065
[ALL CHUCKLE]

218
00:22:02,421 --> 00:22:05,990
[MAN]: Do "A Patch of Land".
It's not a song.

219
00:22:05,991 --> 00:22:08,293
[ALL LAUGH]

220
00:22:08,294 --> 00:22:10,505
[GUITARS PLAYING]

221
00:22:12,665 --> 00:22:14,532
Good morning.
Good morning.

222
00:22:14,533 --> 00:22:16,835
- How are you feeling today?
- Good.

223
00:22:16,836 --> 00:22:19,470
Yeah? Good.

224
00:22:19,471 --> 00:22:24,375
So, uh, I stopped by the juice place
and I got you a kale with ginseng.

225
00:22:24,376 --> 00:22:27,850
Do you mind just putting your feet
off the counter?

226
00:22:28,013 --> 00:22:30,849
I got you a kale and ginseng
because it's just...

227
00:22:30,850 --> 00:22:33,630
I don't know,
I thought it might make you feel better.

228
00:22:34,019 --> 00:22:36,988
If that doesn't appeal to you,
I also got a pineapple orange.

229
00:22:36,989 --> 00:22:40,058
Yeah, that might be better. Thank you.
Okay.

230
00:22:40,059 --> 00:22:44,830
Oh, and I also got you protein bars,
just in case you want a snack.

231
00:22:48,968 --> 00:22:51,544
Why is the house so big?

232
00:22:51,871 --> 00:22:53,738
The house isn't so big.

233
00:22:53,739 --> 00:22:56,074
It's big for two people.

234
00:22:56,075 --> 00:22:58,910
Well, yeah, but we like to entertain.

235
00:22:58,911 --> 00:23:01,379
And sometimes friends come up
for the weekend...

236
00:23:01,380 --> 00:23:04,315
sometimes we have parties.
It's just nice to have space.

237
00:23:04,316 --> 00:23:06,684
So no one else lives here?

238
00:23:06,685 --> 00:23:09,488
Of course no one else lives here.

239
00:23:27,506 --> 00:23:30,375
You're married?
Yeah.

240
00:23:30,376 --> 00:23:33,680
When?
April.

241
00:23:34,947 --> 00:23:38,283
I tried calling you, but, uh, apparently
you got rid of your cell phone.

242
00:23:38,284 --> 00:23:40,018
I lost it.

243
00:23:40,019 --> 00:23:43,421
You didn't think to get a new one?
I got used to not having one.

244
00:23:43,422 --> 00:23:45,723
- [TED]: Cocktails, anyone?
- No, thank you.

245
00:23:45,724 --> 00:23:48,504
Martha?
Mm-mm.

246
00:23:52,965 --> 00:23:56,234
Was it a big wedding?
About 40 people.

247
00:23:56,235 --> 00:23:57,936
Mostly Ted's family.

248
00:23:57,937 --> 00:24:00,438
- Did Aunt Dora come?
- Ha, yes.

249
00:24:00,439 --> 00:24:03,274
Did she smoke like a chimney
and complain about everything?

250
00:24:03,275 --> 00:24:05,977
- She's not that bad.
- You didn't have to live with her.

251
00:24:05,978 --> 00:24:07,278
[TED]:
You lived with Dora?

252
00:24:07,279 --> 00:24:09,752
